docs.abstract: Brett Hankison, a former Louisville police detective, is facing three charges of wanton endangerment after the authorities said he fired “blindly” into Ms. Taylor’s apartment.
docs.snippet: Brett Hankison, a former Louisville police detective, is facing three charges of wanton endangerment after the authorities said he fired “blindly” into Ms. Taylor’s apartment.
docs.lead_paragraph: The only trial to emerge from the nighttime police raid that killed Breonna Taylor began on Wednesday, but the case centers not on an officer who shot her, but rather on a former police detective accused of recklessly endangering her neighbors with a hail of bullets that inadvertently hit their apartment in Louisville, Ky.

headline.main: Officer Accused of Recklessly Firing in Breonna Taylor Raid Goes on Trial
headline.print_headline: Officer Accused of Recklessly Firing During Taylor Raid Goes on Trial

byline.original: By Giulia Heyward and Nicholas Bogel-Burroughs

docs.abstract: The court did not say which of the three defendants was infected with the coronavirus. The judge paused the proceedings at least until Monday.
docs.snippet: The court did not say which of the three defendants was infected with the coronavirus. The judge paused the proceedings at least until Monday.
docs.lead_paragraph: ST. PAUL, Minn. — The federal trial of three former Minneapolis police officers charged with violating George Floyd’s civil rights was postponed on Wednesday after one of the former officers tested positive for the coronavirus, court officials said.

headline.main: The federal trial of three former officers in the killing of George Floyd is postponed after one tests positive.

docs.abstract: A large crowd of demonstrators gathered downtown days after the fatal shooting of Amir Locke, 22.
docs.snippet: A large crowd of demonstrators gathered downtown days after the fatal shooting of Amir Locke, 22.
docs.lead_paragraph: MINNEAPOLIS — Chanting the name of Amir Locke, a large crowd of protesters marched in frigid weather in downtown Minneapolis on Saturday to voice exasperation and anger over the conduct of law enforcement officers, nearly two years after the murder of George Floyd.

headline.main: ‘We Need Something Different’: Protesters March in Minneapolis After Police Killing
headline.print_headline: Police Killing Sets Off Protests in Minneapolis

byline.original: By Jay Senter, Sophie Kasakove and Sergio Olmos

docs.abstract: The men were previously convicted of murder. The government is now trying to build a case that racism fueled their actions.
docs.snippet: The men were previously convicted of murder. The government is now trying to build a case that racism fueled their actions.
docs.lead_paragraph: BRUNSWICK, Ga. — Prosecutors in the hate crimes trial of Ahmaud Arbery’s pursuers on Tuesday focused on showing the ways in which the government believes that the defendants’ racism manifested itself on the day Mr. Arbery was murdered — including the fact that they did not try to help him as he lay dying in the street.

headline.main: Prosecutors Focus on Arbery Killers’ Failure to Help as He Lay Dying
headline.print_headline: Prosecutors Center Argument on Arbery Killers’ Failure to Help as He Lay Dying

byline.original: By Tariro Mzezewa and Richard Fausset

docs.abstract: Visibility is one thing. Actually mustering the power to fundamentally rearrange society — that is something else.
docs.snippet: Visibility is one thing. Actually mustering the power to fundamentally rearrange society — that is something else.
docs.lead_paragraph: Consider the Black Lives Matter lawn sign.

docs.abstract: Gregory and Travis McMichael had previously agreed to plead guilty, but a federal judge rejected the deal, which offered 30-year sentences. Jury selection is set to begin on Monday.
docs.snippet: Gregory and Travis McMichael had previously agreed to plead guilty, but a federal judge rejected the deal, which offered 30-year sentences. Jury selection is set to begin on Monday.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — Travis and Gregory McMichael, two of the three men convicted in state court of murdering Ahmaud Arbery, have withdrawn guilty pleas in their federal hate crimes case, clearing the way for a trial that will once again revisit the afternoon two years ago when they chased Mr. Arbery, a Black man, through their South Georgia neighborhood, a chase that ended with three shotgun blasts, and Mr. Arbery dead on the pavement.

headline.main: Hate Crimes Trial to Proceed After Arbery Killers Withdraw Guilty Pleas
headline.print_headline: 2 Men Withdraw Guilty Pleas in Arbery Killing

docs.abstract: With violent crime rates rising and elections looming, progressive prosecutors are facing resistance to their plans to roll back stricter crime policies of the 1990s.
docs.snippet: With violent crime rates rising and elections looming, progressive prosecutors are facing resistance to their plans to roll back stricter crime policies of the 1990s.
docs.lead_paragraph: Four years ago, progressive prosecutors were in the sweet spot of Democratic politics. Aligned with the growing Black Lives Matter movement but pragmatic enough to draw establishment support, they racked up wins in cities across the country.

headline.main: They Wanted to Roll Back Tough-on-Crime Policies. Then Violent Crime Surged.
headline.print_headline: Progressive Prosecutors Feel Pressure On Crime

docs.abstract: Jurors delivered a swift verdict after a weeklong trial in which prosecutors presented voluminous evidence of the men’s racist beliefs and language.
docs.snippet: Jurors delivered a swift verdict after a weeklong trial in which prosecutors presented voluminous evidence of the men’s racist beliefs and language.
docs.lead_paragraph: BRUNSWICK, Ga. — A jury on Tuesday found the three white Georgia men who murdered Ahmaud Arbery guilty of a federal hate crime, determining that they were motivated by racism when they chased the 25-year-old Black man through their neighborhood.

headline.main: Three Men Are Found Guilty of Hate Crimes in Arbery Killing
headline.print_headline: Federal Jury Finds That Arbery Killing Was Motivated by Racism

byline.original: By Tariro Mzezewa, Audra D. S. Burch and Richard Fausset

docs.abstract: In closing arguments, prosecutors said that Ahmaud Arbery’s killers were motivated by racism. Lawyers for the defendants said the men had suspected him of committing crimes.
docs.snippet: In closing arguments, prosecutors said that Ahmaud Arbery’s killers were motivated by racism. Lawyers for the defendants said the men had suspected him of committing crimes.
docs.lead_paragraph: BRUNSWICK, Ga. — A federal prosecutor in the hate crimes trial for the three white men who murdered Ahmaud Arbery told the jury in closing arguments on Monday that the defendants had targeted Mr. Arbery because of his race and did not help him after he was shot because they considered him to be “subhuman.”

headline.main: Hate Crimes Case in Arbery Murder Goes to Jury
headline.print_headline: Jury to Decide Whether Racism  Motivated 3 Men to Kill Arbery

byline.original: By Tariro Mzezewa and Richard Fausset

docs.abstract: A federal jury will hear closing arguments on Monday and then determine whether the three men convicted of Ahmaud Arbery’s murder killed him because he was Black.
docs.snippet: A federal jury will hear closing arguments on Monday and then determine whether the three men convicted of Ahmaud Arbery’s murder killed him because he was Black.
docs.lead_paragraph: BRUNSWICK, Ga. — Defense lawyers in the hate crimes trial of the three white men convicted of murdering Ahmaud Arbery rested their case on Friday after calling just a single witness.

headline.main: After Calling One Witness, Defense Rests in Arbery Hate Crimes Trial
headline.print_headline: Defense Team Rests Case in Arbery Hate Crimes Trial
